The fourth argument is directed to the same point as the second: we see, in the case of rain which is converted into the fruits of the earth, an instance osa res which perishes, but whose atonis survive. But the philosopher has had his innings, and the poet now comes sorward. What follows is not philosophy but mythology taken from the Greek dramatists: it describes the ‘mystic marriage' (ἱερὸς γάμος) between the sky and the earth, to which all life and joy is due; and this gives occasion for a picture of spring, as beautiful in its simplicity as any poet ever drew.
